
The simple mental model
OpenTelemetry is the wiring inside your app
Prometheus is where your app’s operational metrics live
MLflow is where your LLM/agent traces, prompt lineage, evaluations, and comparisons live

OpenTelemetry is the standard layer that instruments Python apps and emits traces, metrics, and logs. Prometheus supports OTLP ingestion for OpenTelemetry metrics. MLflow’s tracing stack is OpenTelemetry-compatible and its tracing SDK is built on top of OpenTelemetry.

How that maps to your codebase

For your FastMCP app, the request flow is:

frontend or curl
→ backend/main.py
→ backend/agent/orchestrator.py
→ LLM call(s)
→ MCP tool call(s)
→ response returned

And the observability flow should be:

your app code
→ OpenTelemetry instrumentation in main.py, collector.py, and orchestrator.py
→ Prometheus for numeric operational metrics
→ MLflow for rich LLM/agent traces and later eval workflows

That works well because OpenTelemetry is designed for manual instrumentation in Python apps, Prometheus is designed to store time-series operational metrics, and MLflow is designed to trace LLM/agent steps including inputs, outputs, metadata, latency, and costs.

What each piece does in your project
OpenTelemetry

In your project, OpenTelemetry should stay inside:

backend/main.py
backend/metrics/collector.py
backend/agent/orchestrator.py

Its job is to create the trace/span tree and emit counters/histograms.

So for one /chat request, OpenTelemetry gives you spans like:

chat.request
orchestrator.respond
skill.select
skill.load
llm.call
mcp.tool.call

And it gives you metrics like:

request count
request latency
LLM call count
LLM latency
token counts
tool call count
tool latency
tool failures

That matches OpenTelemetry’s role in Python: you initialize the SDK once, then instrument the interesting code paths to emit traces and metrics.

Prometheus

Prometheus should be the place you look for “is the app healthy?”

For your project, Prometheus should answer questions like:

How many chat requests are happening?
What is p95 latency?
How many LLM calls per request?
Which MCP tool is slowest?
How many tool failures happened today?
Are token counts trending up?

Prometheus is a monitoring and alerting system that stores metrics as time series, and it can ingest OpenTelemetry metrics through OTLP over HTTP.

So in your architecture, Prometheus is not where you inspect full LLM conversations or prompt details. It is where you inspect aggregated metrics over time.

MLflow

MLflow should be the place you look for “how is the AI behavior doing?”

For your project, MLflow should eventually hold:

LLM/agent traces
prompt version or prompt alias used
model used
tool sequence used
bad/good trace examples
benchmark results
prompt comparisons
model comparisons
eval datasets built from production traces

MLflow’s tracing is OpenTelemetry-compatible, and MLflow can ingest OpenTelemetry traces through an OTLP endpoint. MLflow also positions traces as useful for building high-quality evaluation datasets from real production traffic.

So in your project, MLflow is the AI quality / experimentation / eval system, not the main operational dashboard.

How the pieces relate in your project

Right now, in phase 1, your architecture is basically:

backend/main.py starts the request
→ collector.py starts OTEL request telemetry
→ orchestrator.py creates child spans for LLM/tool work
→ metrics are emitted through OpenTelemetry
→ JSONL still gets written locally

As you grow it, it should become:

OpenTelemetry in app
→ Prometheus receives the metrics
→ MLflow receives the traces

That split works because Prometheus is best at time-series service metrics, while MLflow is best at LLM/agent trace understanding and evaluation workflows.

What each system is for, in one sentence

For your project:

OpenTelemetry: “capture what happened during a request”
Prometheus: “show me operational numbers over time”
MLflow: “show me how the agent behaved and help me improve it”
What you should look at in each system

Use Prometheus/Grafana when you want:

latency dashboards
throughput
failure rate
tool usage rate
alerts

Use MLflow when you want:

trace-by-trace debugging
compare prompt versions
compare models
analyze bad answers
build eval sets from real traces

Use your local JSONL file when you want:

simple local debugging
backward compatibility with your current scripts
quick ad hoc inspection without backend infrastructure
The architecture I recommend for your project going forward

Phase 1, which you already started:

OpenTelemetry inside main.py, collector.py, orchestrator.py
JSONL kept as-is

Phase 2:

send OTEL metrics to Prometheus
add dashboards in Grafana

Phase 3:

send traces to MLflow
connect benchmark scripts and quality.py to MLflow runs
add prompt/model comparison workflows

That staged approach fits your project well because your core runtime facts are already concentrated in just a few files, and MLflow can sit alongside OpenTelemetry rather than replacing it.

The shortest architecture summary

For your FastMCP project:

OpenTelemetry gets added to the request path in your backend
Prometheus becomes the home for the app’s numeric health metrics
MLflow becomes the home for the LLM/agent traces, comparisons, and eval work

So your app does the work once, through OpenTelemetry, and then:

Prometheus tells you whether the system is healthy
MLflow tells you whether the AI behavior is good

